{"id": "e8a21a3b926d4305b3fc7a2686a28f50", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 05:37:01", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Thought: The proposed topic directly addresses a critical gap in causal graph representation learning—namely, the reliance on pre-existing or assumed instrumental variables (IVs) that are often unavailable or invalid due to latent confounding. By reframing IVs as *learned features* generated from unconditional moment restrictions (UMRs) rooted in graph structure (e.g., temporal lags, topological separation, symmetry), this research introduces a novel and testable mechanism for deconfounding relational data. The integration of UMR-preserving objectives into GNN training enables algorithmic construction of valid instruments, transforming a fundamental assumption into an optimizable component of the model. This approach is innovative, grounded in causal theory, and scalable to real-world applications such as drug discovery or social network analysis where confounding is structural and unobserved. Furthermore, the plan to prototype on synthetic stochastic block models ensures methodological rigor and interpretability during validation. Given its potential to shift how causality is approached in graph AI—from assuming instruments to generating them—the topic represents a high-impact direction with strong theoretical and practical foundations.\n\nTopic: ```json{\"Selected Topic\": \"Algorithmic Generation of Instrumental Variables via Unconditional Moment Restrictions in Graph Representation Learning\"}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[97mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "baf4c229508240d9ae7431bda5123049", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 05:37:06", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "The team has finalized the selection of a high-impact research topic: *Algorithmic Generation of Instrumental Variables via Unconditional Moment Restrictions in Graph Representation Learning*. This approach addresses latent confounding in causal graph neural networks by algorithmically generating valid instrumental variables (IVs) from structural features such as temporal lags, topological separation, or symmetry—formalized as unconditional moment restrictions (UMRs). Instead of relying on assumed or observed instruments, the method integrates UMR-preserving objectives into GNN training, making instrument validity an optimizable property. The research will be prototyped on synthetic graphs (e.g., stochastic block models with latent confounders), enabling rigorous evaluation of causal estimation accuracy. The direction is theoretically grounded, empirically testable, and opens pathways for innovation in causal AI, with immediate next steps focused on implementation and validation.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[97mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
